04959nam a22008535i 9789048544417DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a9789048544417  a(DE-B1597)576206  a(OCoLC)1242879762  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aREL0370002bisacsh04a297.095957051 aAbdullah, Walid Jumblatt, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIslam in a Secular State :bMuslim Activism in Singapore /cWalid Jumblatt Abdullah. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion and Society in Asia ;v900tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- t1 Introduction: The State, Islam, and Muslim Activism in Singapore -- t2 Muslim Activism: A Survey across the World -- t3 Argument: Political Opportunities and Muslim Strategies -- t4 The Ulama: Pragmatism and Political Acquiescence -- t5 Liberal Activists: Playing by the System and Making Gains -- t6 The Conservative Dilemma: To Challenge or Accept State Proclamations? -- t7 Conclusion -- tCombined Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe overtly secular state of Singapore has unapologetically maintained an authoritarian approach to governance in the realm of religion. Islam is particularly managed by the state. Muslim activists thus have to meticulously navigate these realities - in addition to being a minority community - in order to maximize their influence in the political system. Significantly, Muslim activists are not a monolith: there exists a multitude of political and theological differences amongst them. This study analyses the following categories of Muslim activists: Islamic religious scholars (ulama), liberal Muslims, and the more conservative-minded individuals. Due to constricting political realities, many activists attempt to align themselves with the state, and call upon the state to be an arbiter in their disagreements with other factions. Though there are activists who challenge the state, these are by far in the minority, and are typically unable to assert their influence in a sustained manner.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aAsian Studies. 4aIslam. 4aPolitics and Government. 4aReligion and Theology. 4aSociology and Social History. 4aSouth East Asia. 7aRELIGION / Islam / General.2bisacsh  aAuthoritarianism.  aIslam.  aMuslim Activists.  aSecular State.  aSingapore.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074322708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021 Englishz978311075419308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021z9783110753974oZDB-23-DGF40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978904854441740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048544417423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048544417/original  a978-3-11-074322-7  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-074335-7  DG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075419-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SS